attributes.background:
A government review has concluded that the Royal Mint should ‘mov[e] outside the public sector.’

This move towards privatisation should be opposed, for several reasons: 
• the Mint has performed well in the public sector, turning a financial deficit into a £10 million surplus; there is no evidence to suggest that the proposed change would benefit its customers or employees;
• it is a world-renowned ‘brand’, with a 1,000-year history, whose prestige and service standards should not be jeopardised;  
• privatisation usually benefits only the companies taking on public sector work, leaving users and taxpayers with a poorer, and costlier, service; 
• the Mint employs 750 staff in South Wales, an economically deprived area hit hard by the recession; their livelihood could be at risk if a new owner, seeking to boost profits, were to cut back on jobs, pay and conditions, or even transfer the work abroad;  
• in a recession, it is unwise to make public services more dependent on private capital.
